    quiz: [{ question: "An NP is evaluating a 17-year-old with primary amenorrhea, normal breast development, absent pubic hair, and pelvic MRI showing absent uterus with bilateral inguinal masses. Karyotype is 46,XY. Testosterone is 600 ng/dL. What is the most important diagnostic test to differentiate complete AIS from 5-alpha reductase deficiency?", options: ["Serum estradiol level", "Testosterone-to-DHT ratio", "FSH level", "Pelvic CT scan"], correct: 1, rationale: "The testosterone-to-DHT ratio is the key differentiating test between AIS and 5-alpha reductase deficiency (5-ARD). In AIS, 5-alpha reductase function is intact so testosterone is normally converted to DHT, giving a normal ratio. In 5-ARD, conversion is impaired, resulting in a markedly elevated testosterone-to-DHT ratio (>20:1). This distinction is critical because 5-ARD patients will virilize at puberty due to the direct action of testosterone at high concentrations, while CAIS patients will not virilize at all. Management and gender outcomes differ significantly between these two conditions." }]
